When you try to resuscitate a person who has been drowning can you please clear their airway? There is no point in resuscitating people if their lungs are full of water. If you do nothing else at least clear a person's airway and put them in a recovery position, on their side.  This is such a common mistake in movies and on TV. Oxygen can not get into your lungs if it is full of water. Before attempting some sort of CPR then clear the airway first. Otherwise compressing the heart is pointless.   The order is check for danger. If it is safe for you then check to see if a person is conscious. If not then check or clear the airway. Compressing the heart is the last on the list. Heart compressions are the last thing you do. DRABC.  Danger, response, airway, breathing and then compressions.

And while Galadriel being the main character and focus of the show is not a bad idea, Galadriel obviously has had some adventures in the past considering she is a long lived elf, this is not the right time to do it. Not to say female empowerment in media is a bad thing, it's just lately it seems that instead of creating interesting characters and stories that in turn empower women through good messages and writing, most are very bland, very basic and very to the point and not subtle at all. What a depressingly bad bit of drivel this appears. Honestly, I can't tell if they ever aspired for this to truly be a part of the Tolkien world or if it was always meant to be something else entirely. Aside from all of the obvious lore issues, and generic production design, what I find most disturbing is the utter lack of well-crafted, Tolkien-inspired dialogue. Nothing, not a single spoken word or exchange shared thus far, feels even remotely like something Prof. Tolkien would have ever written. I would not expect the RoP writers to match him, but I had hoped there would at least be moments of beauty and depth. But depressingly, to this point, there is not even the suggestion that they've managed to capture even the barest sense of the tone, texture, or weight of his language. To fail so completely at these most fundamental levels bodes ill for the entire project. I'd simply ask the show's creators and producers one question; knowing as you must just how unhappy and disappointed J.R.R. Tolkien would have been with every element of this series, how can you feel anything but embarrassment and regret having treated his timeless masterwork so shamefully? Does respect for a fellow artist's life's work mean nothing to you? While you may protest or insist that you "meant to honor him," the truth of one's intention is demonstrated most clearly not by what you say but by what you *DO.* Sadly, what you've done in this case is to expose yourselves as nothing more than opportunistic grave robbers... stealing a treasure of the past and trading your soul for a few pieces of gold. What a profoundly sad insult and exploitation of a work that brought joy to millions of people all over the world.

üìö‚ÄúMaria Romanov After 17 July 1918‚Äù

In a sense, the First World War was the battle of cousins. The financiers of the war decided to erase the last traces of the Russian Empire from history. They had already identified the most suitable employer to achieve their goals. Kaiser Wilhelm the second.
They knew the Kaiser's weakness for Tsarina Aleksandra Fyodorovna, who was the wife of the last Russian Tsar Nicholas the second.
It didn't take long for the Kaiser to find the right shooter for the job. He was Vladimir Ilyich Ulyanov, who was later known as Lenin.
Lenin's brother Aleksandr Ulyanov was executed for the assassination of Tsar Alexander III.
According to the agreements of the Kaiser and Lenin, the Tsar would be killed. The Tsar's family would be sent to the Kaiser. But Lenin did not obey the agreement, thinking that the Kaiser would betray him.
The execution, which took place on July 17, 1918, at 01:00, was concluded as neither the Kaiser nor Lenin had planned.
Maria and her brother Alexei were able to survive with the help of the young Prince, whom Maria had met at a prom in Romania.
This book is about the lives of Maria and Alexei after July 17, 1918.
